WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:02.200
I'm not Mike Stackhouse.

00:00:02.200 --> 00:00:03.320
He's the one who wrote this.

00:00:03.320 --> 00:00:04.960
Unfortunately, he wasn't able to make it.

00:00:04.960 --> 00:00:06.400
So if I do a terrible job,

00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:08.880
just send all your complaints to him.

00:00:08.880 --> 00:00:09.720
Neither am I.

00:00:09.720 --> 00:00:12.920
I'm not Mike, and since most of you probably know that,

00:00:14.680 --> 00:00:19.040
but they're the kind of two that really worked

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:21.040
on what we're going to talk about today.

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:23.959
And that's really, we're going to talk about

00:00:23.959 --> 00:00:28.320
how to sort of build a system around Shiny

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:31.040
that lets us build a lot of applications

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:35.840
that are kind of follow a similar template.

00:00:37.720 --> 00:00:41.000
So not everybody is probably in pharma.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:43.720
So a little background is in pharma,

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:47.400
there's this thing called GXP or good clinical practice.

00:00:48.799 --> 00:00:51.320
There's a lot more restraints on things that you can do.

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:53.480
Like data access is a really big thing

00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:56.400
because you don't want anybody accessing the data.

00:00:57.400 --> 00:01:02.400
And it can be hard to do new things and add new systems.

00:01:04.279 --> 00:01:06.320
So some of the implications of that

00:01:06.320 --> 00:01:09.040
is you've kind of just got to work with what you have.

00:01:10.160 --> 00:01:12.839
One of the things being like your data is often

00:01:12.839 --> 00:01:16.000
on a file system versus a database.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:18.680
So that's kind of where we're coming at with this.

00:01:18.680 --> 00:01:20.000
So it might look a little bit unusual

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:21.839
if you're not in pharma,

00:01:21.839 --> 00:01:24.879
but the reason why we're focused on file systems is that.

00:01:27.400 --> 00:01:31.080
So alternative title would be more like

00:01:31.080 --> 00:01:33.879
how to make a reusable app

00:01:33.879 --> 00:01:38.000
for within the constraints of pharma.

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:46.160
So the main idea here is let's say

00:01:46.559 --> 00:01:48.639
you had a biometrics lead.

00:01:48.639 --> 00:01:52.360
They have, we have an app for called for study A.

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:53.440
They see it, they like it and say,

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:55.519
hey, I want that for study B as well.

00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:02.400
So one thing you could do is like copy the app for study A

00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:04.440
and turn it into study B

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:09.399
and then change the things that are a little bit different.

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:16.720
But you can run into issues when you find a bug

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:18.720
in the copy study B.

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:20.880
What are you going to do then?

00:02:20.880 --> 00:02:22.240
Well, you could fix the bug

00:02:23.320 --> 00:02:25.119
and then copy it back into study A.

00:02:26.119 --> 00:02:27.399
That could work.

00:02:28.520 --> 00:02:32.039
But if you have study C, D, E, F,

00:02:32.039 --> 00:02:33.399
it's going to be a lot more challenging

00:02:33.399 --> 00:02:37.039
and it's going to be a lot easier to make mistakes

00:02:37.039 --> 00:02:38.119
and mix things up.

00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:43.960
So really your user story might be,

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:49.360
I also want to make an app for study A or for study C

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:52.039
and I want to include a new chart as well.

00:02:52.039 --> 00:02:53.759
I want something a little bit different,

00:02:53.800 --> 00:02:55.199
not quite the same thing.

00:02:59.119 --> 00:03:01.559
So again, we could copy and paste.

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:10.639
But how do we get that across?

00:03:10.639 --> 00:03:12.360
So let's say it's a new chart that we're adding.

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:14.479
How do we get that to all these different applications

00:03:14.479 --> 00:03:15.320
we have?

00:03:15.320 --> 00:03:16.360
We don't just have study A, B, and C.

00:03:16.360 --> 00:03:17.759
We have a dozen.

00:03:19.320 --> 00:03:21.559
Copying, pasting to all these places

00:03:21.559 --> 00:03:23.160
is not really a good idea.

00:03:24.600 --> 00:03:26.479
So kind of the focus here today

00:03:26.479 --> 00:03:30.440
is how to generalize this idea of having an app

00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:32.880
that you want to be able to adapt

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:34.639
and do just little tweaks.

00:03:34.639 --> 00:03:36.240
And how do you propagate those changes

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:37.800
and to keep everything in sync?

00:03:39.119 --> 00:03:41.440
So the way we recommend doing this

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:43.639
is your original app,

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:46.800
turn it into a package

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:49.360
that you can then use that package as a dependency

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:51.600
and all your other like child apps.

00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:54.199
So the idea is kind of like a template.

00:03:54.199 --> 00:03:55.880
Your main app is like a template

00:03:57.759 --> 00:03:59.119
that's included in your package.

00:03:59.119 --> 00:04:01.279
Maybe you have modules that you export for your package.

00:04:01.279 --> 00:04:03.679
You use those throughout all the child apps.

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:09.960
So if you find a bug in one of your child apps,

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:12.399
you don't have to go and update everywhere.

00:04:12.399 --> 00:04:15.080
You just go update your parent package

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:18.799
and then you can propagate that out to all the children.

00:04:18.799 --> 00:04:21.239
All you have to do is update the package version.

00:04:22.239 --> 00:04:27.239
And another thing, another aspect kind of related data

00:04:32.079 --> 00:04:34.880
is you want to be able to configure

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:36.440
your app slightly differently.

00:04:38.200 --> 00:04:40.480
Again, they're not going to be exact copies.

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:43.200
You want a little flexibility there to tweak them.

00:04:47.480 --> 00:04:50.480
So in terms of the data,

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:53.880
what we recommend doing is doing as much as you can

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:55.239
of any of your data wrangling,

00:04:55.239 --> 00:04:58.440
data processing outside of the app.

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:00.679
And Posit Connect has this really cool feature

00:05:00.679 --> 00:05:03.079
where you can run things on a schedule.

00:05:03.079 --> 00:05:05.040
So you can put it in like an R script

00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:07.839
or R Markdown script, for example,

00:05:07.839 --> 00:05:11.640
and then run that whenever your data updates

00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:12.480
and then your app,

00:05:12.480 --> 00:05:14.839
so that way you never have to actually change your app.

00:05:14.839 --> 00:05:19.839
So, but then you have the problem of,

00:05:20.839 --> 00:05:23.200
if your data is a little bit different

00:05:23.200 --> 00:05:25.760
between each application,

00:05:25.760 --> 00:05:28.320
how does the application know how to use it?

00:05:28.320 --> 00:05:33.320
So the way you connect your data to your application

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:38.200
and the way you generalize these applications

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:40.799
that we recommend is using a YAML file

00:05:40.799 --> 00:05:43.320
that basically specifies all your configuration.

00:05:44.320 --> 00:05:48.200
So for example, you might use as your subject variable,

00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:49.399
your subject ID,

00:05:49.399 --> 00:05:51.799
maybe another study uses a different variable.

00:05:51.799 --> 00:05:53.839
All you have to do is change that one place

00:05:53.839 --> 00:05:55.640
and then your app's going to work

00:05:56.880 --> 00:06:00.119
just like your child app is going to work.

00:06:02.040 --> 00:06:05.799
So within the app, instead of calling,

00:06:05.799 --> 00:06:08.079
you know, instead of saying you subject ID,

00:06:08.079 --> 00:06:09.679
I want to use that column,

00:06:09.679 --> 00:06:12.480
you do more on the bottom here where you say,

00:06:12.839 --> 00:06:16.600
you just call the YAML key

00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:18.600
and then it returns a value for you.

00:06:18.600 --> 00:06:19.720
So you don't have to,

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:22.160
it's more like a function argument

00:06:22.160 --> 00:06:25.679
than specifying the column name.

00:06:27.799 --> 00:06:31.279
So each child app or child repository

00:06:31.279 --> 00:06:32.920
is going to have like three main components.

00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:35.160
You're going to have the app,

00:06:35.160 --> 00:06:37.839
your markdown or R script

00:06:37.839 --> 00:06:40.000
that's going to run your data processing

00:06:40.040 --> 00:06:41.600
and your YAML file

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:46.600
that's going to configure the details of application.

00:06:51.880 --> 00:06:54.799
And so by having it as a package,

00:06:54.799 --> 00:06:56.480
we can version the package

00:06:56.480 --> 00:06:57.679
so we can have different apps

00:06:57.679 --> 00:06:59.920
that depend on different versions.

00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:02.160
Maybe you have an app that you don't want to update,

00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:04.399
you can keep it on an old version.

00:07:04.399 --> 00:07:06.359
Maybe you, you know, another study team

00:07:06.359 --> 00:07:09.079
wants the most current version.

00:07:10.679 --> 00:07:12.160
And it also helps for validation

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:15.559
because you really need to just test the parent package,

00:07:15.559 --> 00:07:16.920
validate that.

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:18.880
And then for any child app,

00:07:18.880 --> 00:07:21.600
you just, all you need to look at is the differences,

00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:24.040
where you don't need to run all your tests again.

00:07:27.320 --> 00:07:32.320
So Mike and Maya created this package here called MAT

00:07:33.559 --> 00:07:35.959
that you can find on the Torsys GitHub.

00:07:35.959 --> 00:07:40.640
And it's an example of how to implement these ideas.

00:07:40.640 --> 00:07:42.320
So it's really, really basic

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:44.760
and it's in early development right now,

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:46.279
but it has the functionality

00:07:46.279 --> 00:07:49.119
to where you can have your parent app,

00:07:49.119 --> 00:07:50.239
like your template,

00:07:51.079 --> 00:07:54.119
generate your child app from that.

00:07:54.119 --> 00:07:57.399
There are some example YAML files in there

00:07:57.399 --> 00:07:59.559
so you could see what kind of metadata you'd want to use

00:07:59.559 --> 00:08:02.519
and get that mapping from data to app.

00:08:03.480 --> 00:08:07.480
And a template for running your data processing.

00:08:14.079 --> 00:08:19.079
So they're planning on expanding it

00:08:22.359 --> 00:08:24.399
as basically, as we work,

00:08:26.640 --> 00:08:29.480
as we use this idea and find problems

00:08:29.480 --> 00:08:30.600
or find better ways to do it,

00:08:30.600 --> 00:08:34.000
they're gonna implement it in this package.

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:42.640
So to recap, the benefits of this generalized strategy

00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:46.520
is you only have one place that you need to make updates.

00:08:46.520 --> 00:08:50.000
And you can use the existing system

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:51.719
that we have of pack and versioning

00:08:51.719 --> 00:08:54.400
for help and validation.

00:08:55.520 --> 00:08:57.840
And it also gives you flexibility.

00:08:57.840 --> 00:09:00.440
So it's not, your child apps are not exact copy,

00:09:01.280 --> 00:09:04.320
but you have some different tweaks

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:06.960
that you can run, different features that you can use.

00:09:14.599 --> 00:09:15.599
That's all I've got.

00:09:17.039 --> 00:09:22.039
Thank you so much, Andrew.

00:09:22.359 --> 00:09:25.359
I have a question from someone in our virtual audience.

00:09:25.359 --> 00:09:28.359
Do you mind talking a little bit more

00:09:28.359 --> 00:09:31.359
about caching a Shiny app for faster startup times?

00:09:31.359 --> 00:09:33.359
Yeah, so it's caching the data.

00:09:33.359 --> 00:09:36.359
So let's say, I mean, if your data updates,

00:09:36.359 --> 00:09:39.359
maybe once a week, you'd run your job once a week

00:09:39.359 --> 00:09:42.359
to do whatever wrangling you need to do

00:09:42.359 --> 00:09:43.359
and then you save that.

00:09:43.359 --> 00:09:46.359
So that way you're not doing it within the app itself.

00:09:46.359 --> 00:09:48.359
So that's a great question.

00:09:48.679 --> 00:09:49.679
Right, right.

00:09:49.679 --> 00:09:53.679
And you mentioned that using a scheduled script

00:09:53.679 --> 00:09:55.679
in R Markdown would be a good way to do that?

00:09:55.679 --> 00:09:59.679
Yeah, and if you look at the packages as an example,

00:09:59.679 --> 00:10:03.679
that's how we're doing it because it's easy.

00:10:03.679 --> 00:10:06.679
Most likely, if you're doing a lot of Shiny app development,

00:10:06.679 --> 00:10:08.679
you probably have PositConnect.

00:10:08.679 --> 00:10:11.679
And it's just an easy way to use the existing tools.

00:10:11.679 --> 00:10:12.679
Awesome.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:16.000
What are your guidelines or general guidelines

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:19.000
on how much of the app code goes in the package?

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
It's pretty much as much as possible.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:25.000
Right.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.000
Right, because anything you're going to want to generalize.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:29.000
Right.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
Do you rely on the Gollum framework

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
to package the initialization?

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.000
Yeah, we rely on the Gollum framework.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.000
We rely on the Gollum framework

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:41.000
to package the initialization.

00:10:41.320 --> 00:10:43.320
Do you rely on the Gollum framework

00:10:43.320 --> 00:10:45.320
to package the initial app?

00:10:45.320 --> 00:10:47.320
I mean, that's up to you.

00:10:47.320 --> 00:10:49.320
I think the MAD package has support

00:10:49.320 --> 00:10:51.320
for setting up for Gollum and for Rhino,

00:10:51.320 --> 00:10:53.320
maybe something else.

00:10:53.320 --> 00:10:56.320
It doesn't really take an opinion on that.

00:10:56.320 --> 00:10:57.320
Okay.

00:10:58.320 --> 00:11:01.320
And I have one more question here.

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:06.320
Can you say a few words about the various Shiny frameworks,

00:11:06.320 --> 00:11:08.320
Gollumverse versus Rhinoverse?

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:10.320
Do you prefer one over the other?

00:11:10.640 --> 00:11:12.640
I like both.

00:11:12.640 --> 00:11:14.640
I mostly use Gollum

00:11:14.640 --> 00:11:16.640
because it's been around a little longer

00:11:16.640 --> 00:11:18.640
and that's what I've used.

00:11:18.640 --> 00:11:20.640
I like some of the ideas that Rhino does,

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:22.640
like how you use this box,

00:11:22.640 --> 00:11:24.640
so there's a little bit more control

00:11:24.640 --> 00:11:26.640
over your dependencies.

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:28.640
I just haven't used it a lot in practice.

00:11:28.640 --> 00:11:29.640
Great.

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:31.640
Great, yeah.

00:11:31.640 --> 00:11:33.640
Thank you so much.

00:11:33.640 --> 00:11:35.960
Thank you.

